## Decisions Made
- Split TDD into two independent skills (developing-test-first for discipline, driving-with-tests for strategy): User wanted TDD to be independently usable, and the report identified two distinct concerns — the Red/Green/Refactor cycle vs the surrounding strategy (Orient/Probe/Guard)
- No code examples in developing-test-first: This is a discipline skill, not a technique skill — Claude already knows how to write tests; the skill enforces the "test first" rule
- Keep probing details in reference/probing.md rather than inline: SKILL.md stays focused; CLI examples live in the reference file
- CLAUDE.md/AGENTS.md moved to top of Framework Detection table: Project-explicit test commands are the most reliable detection source
- Description uses 3rd person + trigger phrases (not imperative "Use when" only): Follows creating-skills convention for CSO
- Benchmarked against obra/superpowers repo: Adopted Iron Law pattern, rationalization table, Red Flags section, REQUIRED marker, and Composability section patterns

## Problems Encountered
- skill-creator was initially unavailable for review: Resolved by proceeding with creating-skills checklist manually, then re-reviewed when skill-creator became available
- developing-test-first hit 202 lines (2 over 200 target): Accepted as-is because the Verification Checklist is core content that belongs inline

## Constraints Identified
- SKILL.md must stay under 200 lines (500 hard ceiling): Shared context window resource — drives progressive disclosure into reference/ files
- Description field must contain only triggering conditions, not behavioral instructions: CSO principle from superpowers benchmark — Claude follows description instead of reading full skill when description contains process steps
- All skill content must be in English per project policy: Runtime user-facing output adapts to user language

## Open Questions
- Whether to run eval-driven testing with skill-creator's full benchmark pipeline for these two skills: Deferred for now, qualitative review passed

